'''Rakesh Jhaveri''', also known as '''Pujya Gurudevshri Rakeshbhai''',{{efn-ua|Pujya Gurudevshri and Bhai are honorifics. He is credited in his books by this name. He is also addressed as Bapaji or Sahebji by his followers.}} (born 26 September 1966) is a spiritual leader, mystic,  scholar of [[Jainism]], author and orator from India. Spiritually inclined from the young age, he became a follower of [[Shrimad Rajchandra]], a Jain spiritual teacher. He completed doctoral studies on Shrimad's work ''[[Atma Siddhi|Atmasiddhi]]''. He founded Shrimad Rajchandra Mission, [[Dharampur, Gujarat|Dharampur]] to support his spiritual and social activities.

==Early life==
Rakeshbhai Jhaveri was born in [[Mumbai]], India on 26 September 1966 to Shri Dilip and Rekha Jhaveri, who followed the [[Śvētāmbara|Shwetambara]] [[Murtipujaka]] tradition of Jainism.<ref name=":0">{{cite web|url=https://www.religionworld.in/jain-saint-rakesh-bhai-the-true-successor-of-shrimad-rajchandraji/|title=Jain Saint Rakeshbhai Jhaveri: The True Successor of Shrimad Rajchandraji|author=Shweta|date=|website=Religion World|publisher=ReligionWorld.in|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|accessdate=7 June 2018}}</ref> In 1968, Sahaj Anandji, a monk from [[Rajasthan]] who had established Shrimad Rajchandra Ashram at [[Hampi]], was at [[Palitana]]. Rakeshbhai's parents were influenced by Sahaj Anandji who passed away in 1970 and was succeeded by Mataji.{{snf|Salter|2002|p=101-102}} 

In 1972, Rakeshbhai began his academic studies at Activity High School in Mumbai. From an early age, he was spiritually inclined. His mother and others have recounted miracles prior to and after his birth. From the age of four he began speaking about Jain philosophy. He first encountered Shrimad Rajchandraji when a copy of {{transl|gu|Shrimad Rajchandra Vachanamrut}} fell and he saw the photograph of [[Shrimad Rajchandra]]. He recounted that he went into deep meditation for 72 hours after this incident, which led to {{transl|sa|IAST|jāti smaraṇa gnān}} (recounting of previous lives).{{snf|Salter|2002|p=104}} 

In 1978, Rakeshbhai visited Hampi and stayed for eighteen months.{{snf|Salter|2002|p=103}} A ''[[satsang]]-mandal'' (devotional group) was formed by 1978 and some followers had already started to call him [[Guru]] by 1980.{{snf|Salter|2002|p=105}} During his visit to his aunt in [[Jaipur]], he decided to devote rest of his life to spiritual activities.{{snf|Salter|2002|p=105}} In 1983, he visited Hampi again and stayed there for two years. There he was nominated as Mataji's successor.{{snf|Salter|2002|p=103}} In 1985, he returned to Mumbai upon his parents' request and started studying religious texts, practicing [[yoga]] and learning [[Indian classical music]]. He observed silence for twelve hours a day and traveled extensively between 1985 and 1990.{{snf|Salter|2002|p=106-107}}<ref name="TIO2013" /> During this period, the number of followers around him continued to grow.{{snf|Salter|2002|p=106}} During his holidays in [[Nepal]], he decided to pursue the college studies.{{snf|Salter|2002|p=106-107}}

He completed [[Bachelor of Arts|B. A.]] from [[Osmania University]], [[Hyderabad]], in 1988.<ref name=":0"/> In 1989, he visited [[Antwerp]] for his father's treatment where his discourses were attended by increasing number of followers.{{snf|Salter|2002|p=107}} He completed [[Master of Arts|M. A.]] in Philosophy in 1991 from the [[University of Mumbai]].<ref name="TIO2013" /> He started his doctoral studies on ''[[Atmasiddhiji]]'', a spiritual work composed by Shrimad Rajchandraji, in January 1994 under Ramanlal Shah. He was awarded PhD on 2 December 1998 by the University of Mumbai.{{snf|Salter|2002|p=107-108}}<ref name="TIO2013">{{cite news|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/MBAs-doctors-engineers-surrender-soul-to-service-and-prayers/articleshow/18313508.cms?referral=PM|title=MBAs, doctors, engineers surrender soul to service and prayers|last=Chhapia|first=Hemali|date=February 2013|newspaper=Times of India|access-date=2014-02-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160714095854/http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/MBAs-doctors-engineers-surrender-soul-to-service-and-prayers/articleshow/18313508.cms?referral=PM|archive-date=2016-07-14|dead-url=no|df=}}</ref><ref name=":0" /> He had vowed not to give a public discourse until his PhD was completed. He gave his first public discourse in [[Rajkot]] on 13 April 2001.{{snf|Salter|2002|p=107-108}}

==Spiritual life==

[[File:Shrimad Rajchandra Mission Dharampur Ashram.jpg|thumb|Ashram building at Dharampur]]
[[File:Shrimad Rajchandra Mission Dharampur Spiritual Activity.jpg|thumb|Rakeshbhai delivering discourse in Dharampur]]
Rakesh Jhaveri established Shrimad Rajchandra Adhyatmik Satsang Sadhana Kendra in 1994 to organise his followers which was later succeeded by the Shrimad Rajchandra Mission Dharampur. On 13 May 1999, the construction of an [[ashram]] spread across 223 acres at Dharampur was started{{snf|Salter|2002|p=98}}<ref name=":0" /> and was opened in April 2001. The ashram is located on the hillock of Mohangadh which was an estate of the last ruler of the erstwhile [[Dharampur State]].{{snf|Salter|2002|p=99}} In 2002, he started initiating followers, {{transl|gu|Atmarpit}}s, who give up worldly possessions and commit to [[celibacy]].<ref name="TIO2013" /> He gives the series of discourses to his followers at the ashram throughout the year. He gives discourses in Mumbai once a month on {{transl|gu|Shrimad Rajchandra Vachanamrut}}, a compilation of Shrimad Rajchandra's letters, personal diaries and transcriptions of his spiritual discourses.{{snf|Salter|2002|p=98-100}}{{snf|Salter|2002|p=247}} He also prescribes an annual scriptural study schedule to his followers.{{snf|Salter|2002|p=251}}

In November 2016, the Mission produced a play, ''[[Yugpurush (play)|Yugpurush: Mahatma na Mahatma]]'' depicting spiritual relationship between Shrimad Rajchandra and [[Mahatma Gandhi]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Yugpurush: An Inspirational Story of Shrimad Rajchandraji|url=http://www.shrimadrajchandramission.org/asp/download_file.asp?fn=press-yugpurush-mahatma-na-mahatma-janmabhoomi-14th-nov-2016.pdf&fpath=../grace/news/press_articles/images|website=Janmabhoomi|publisher=Janmabhoomi|accessdate=18 November 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161118100930/http://www.shrimadrajchandramission.org/asp/download_file.asp?fn=press-yugpurush-mahatma-na-mahatma-janmabhoomi-14th-nov-2016.pdf&fpath=..%2Fgrace%2Fnews%2Fpress_articles%2Fimages|archive-date=2016-11-18|dead-url=no|df=}}</ref> The Mission opened a science college in Dharampur, Shrimad Rajchandra Vidyapeeth, the same month.<ref>{{cite web|title=Gujarat CM inaugurates Science College at Shrimad Rajchandra Vidyapith in Dharampur|url=http://cmogujarat.gov.in/en/gujarat-cm-inaugurates-science-college-shrimad-rajchandra-vidyapith-dharampur/|website=CMO Gujarat|publisher=CMO Gujarat|accessdate=16 November 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161116231540/http://cmogujarat.gov.in/en/gujarat-cm-inaugurates-science-college-shrimad-rajchandra-vidyapith-dharampur/|archive-date=2016-11-16|dead-url=no|df=}}</ref> In November 2017, the 34-feet tall statue of Shrimad Rajchandra was unveiled at the ashram.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://indianexpress.com/article/cities/ahmedabad/34-feet-statue-of-mahatmas-mentor-unveiled-in-valsad-4921845/|title=34-feet statue of ‘Mahatma’s mentor’ unveiled in Valsad|last1=Das|first1=Preeti|date=4 November 2017|work=|accessdate=7 June 2018|publisher=The Indian Express|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180612140055/http://indianexpress.com/article/cities/ahmedabad/34-feet-statue-of-mahatmas-mentor-unveiled-in-valsad-4921845/|archive-date=2018-06-12|dead-url=no|df=}}</ref> By 2017, the Mission had 102 Satsang centres, 39 Youth Group Centres and 227 Divine Touch Centres worldwide.<ref name=":1">{{cite news|url=http://www.indiawest.com/news/global_indian/modi-releases-commemorative-coins-on-th-birth-anniversary-of-shrimad/article_1170bd9e-6763-11e7-9eee-571ca9ab2522.html|title=Modi Releases Commemorative Coins on 150th Birth Anniversary of Shrimad Rajchandra, Mahatma Gandhi’s Spiritual Guide|date=14 July 2017|accessdate=6 June 2018|publisher=India West|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180705030616/http://www.indiawest.com/news/global_indian/modi-releases-commemorative-coins-on-th-birth-anniversary-of-shrimad/article_1170bd9e-6763-11e7-9eee-571ca9ab2522.html|archive-date=2018-07-05|dead-url=no|df=}}</ref>

He established [[Shrimad Rajchandra Love and Care]] (SRLC); a [[non-governmental organisation]] that provides medical, educational and humanitarian services; in 2003.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.dailyrecord.com/story/news/2017/07/30/indian-charity-comes-parsippany-heads-back/104089864/|title=Indian charity comes to Parsippany and heads back|last1=Reilly|first1=Erin|date=Jul 30, 2017|accessdate=23 August 2017|publisher=USA Today|agency=The Daily Record}}</ref>

==Personal life==
Though he follows several principles of [[Jain monasticism]], such as observing [[Mahavrata|''mahavrata'']]s (major vows), he does not consider himself a monk. He resides with his followers at the ashram in Dharampur and with his family when in Mumbai.<ref name=TIO2013/>

==Recognition==
He was awarded the Gandhi Seva Medal by the [[Gandhi Global Family]], an [[NGO]], in 2017.<ref>{{cite web|title=Gandhi Global Family awards the prestigious ''Gandhi Seva Medal'' to Pujya Gurudevshri|url=http://www.shrimadrajchandramission.org/webcast/wbcst_View.aspx?audioVideoFlag=V&satId=3930&ProdVariantId=16968&catId=367|website=Shrimad Rajchandra Mission Dharampur|publisher=Shrimad Rajchandra Mission Dharampur|accessdate=9 November 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171110005122/http://www.shrimadrajchandramission.org/webcast/wbcst_View.aspx?audioVideoFlag=V&satId=3930&ProdVariantId=16968&catId=367|archive-date=2017-11-10|dead-url=no|df=}}</ref>

